// NOTES FOR CREATING NEW WORKOUTS:
// 
// Sport Selection:
// - "run" - Running workouts
// - "bike" - Cycling workouts (indoor/outdoor agnostic)
// - "swim" - Swimming workouts (pool or open water)
// - "strength" - Resistance training
//
// Phase Guidelines:
// - "base" - Aerobic development, general strength (8-12 weeks)
// - "build" - Threshold work, intensity (6-12 weeks)
// - "peak" - Race-specific preparation (2-4 weeks)
// - "taper" - Sharpening without fatigue (1-2 weeks)
// - "recovery" - Active recovery (1-4 weeks or every 3-4 weeks)
//
// Focus Tags (select 1-4 relevant tags):
// - Training Focus: endurance, aerobic, threshold, tempo, vo2max, sweet_spot
// - Sport-Specific: css (swim), technique, neuromuscular, brick, anaerobic
// - Strength: strength_general, strength_lower, strength_upper, strength_power, 
//   strength_maintenance, strength_run_support, strength_swim
// - Safety: taper_safe, recovery, injury_prevention, mobility
// - Race: race_pace, race_simulation, race_sharpening, pre_race, opener
// - Environment: open_water_suitable (swim only - for continuous/long intervals)
//
// Primary Zone:
// - "z1" - Recovery (50-60% max HR)
// - "z2" - Aerobic (60-70% max HR) 
// - "z3" - Tempo (70-80% max HR)
// - "z4" - Threshold (80-90% max HR)
// - "z5" - VO2max (90-100% max HR)
// - "strength" - Resistance training (use RPE)
//
// Duration & Load Hints:
// - duration_min: Total workout time (must match segment sum)
// - load_hint: Proxy for TSS (typically 50-150% of duration)
//   * Base Z2: ~100% of duration (e.g., 60' = 60 load)
//   * Threshold Z4: ~120-130% of duration (e.g., 60' = 75 load)
//   * VO2max Z5: ~140-150% of duration (e.g., 60' = 85 load)
//   * Taper: ~50-70% of duration (e.g., 30' = 20 load)
//   * Recovery: ~60-80% of duration (e.g., 30' = 20 load)
//
// Segment Types:
// - "warmup" - Gradual intensity build (8-20 min)
// - "steady" - Sustained effort (continuous or tempo)
// - "interval" - Work intervals (threshold, VO2max)
// - "recovery" - Active recovery between intervals
// - "cooldown" - Gradual intensity reduction (5-20 min)
// - "strength" - Resistance training work
//
// Target Types:
// - "zone" - Use for run/bike HR zones
// - "pace" - Use for swim (CSS pace, threshold)
// - "rpe" - Use for strength (RPE 5-8) or neuromuscular work
// - "none" - Use for warmup/cooldown without specific target
//
// Work:Rest Ratios (Evidence-Based):
// - Z4 Threshold: 1:0.3 to 1:0.5 (e.g., 10' work : 3' recovery)
// - Z5 VO2max: 1:1 to 1:1.5 (e.g., 3' work : 3-4' recovery)
// - Sweet Spot: 1:0.2 to 1:0.33 (e.g., 15' work : 5' recovery)
//
// Swimming Environment Tags:
// - Add "open_water_suitable" for:
//   * Continuous endurance swims (2500m+)
//   * Long intervals (200m+ with manageable rest)
//   * Race pace and race simulation workouts
//   * Recovery swims (continuous easy)
// - Pool-only (no tag needed):
//   * Technique/drill sessions
//   * Short intervals (50m, 100m with precise rest)
//   * CSS testing
//   * Taper sharpeners
//
// Safety Requirements:
// - Include warmup for all non-recovery workouts (8-20 min)
// - Include cooldown for all non-recovery workouts (5-20 min)
// - No intensity jumps (Z1→Z5) without gradual build
// - Appropriate recovery between hard intervals
// - Duration realistic for target intensity
//
// Example Durations by Intensity:
// - Z1-Z2 continuous: 20-180 minutes
// - Z3 tempo: 20-90 minutes sustained
// - Z4 threshold intervals: 8-20 minutes per interval
// - Z5 VO2max intervals: 2-4 minutes per interval
// - Taper workouts: 20-50 minutes total
// - Recovery workouts: 20-45 minutes total
//
// Title Format:
// "Sport — Type Duration (Zone)"
// Examples:
// - "Run — Endurance 60′ (Z2)"
// - "Bike — Threshold 3×12′ (Z4)"
// - "Swim — CSS 10×2′ (Z4)"
// - "Strength — Full-Body 45′ (Strength)"
//
// Description Best Practices:
// - 1-2 sentences maximum
// - Explain workout purpose and benefits
// - Use athlete-facing language (not coach jargon)
// - Be motivating and clear
//
// Notes Best Practices:
// - Specific and actionable instructions
// - Athlete-facing language
// - Include key cues (e.g., "nose-breathing OK", "controlled effort")
// - Avoid overly technical terms
// - Keep concise but informative